Browserhacks is a curated collection of browser‑specific CSS and JavaScript
hacks. It documents the quirky selectors, media queries and feature checks that
behave differently across engines, gathered from years of experimentation and
community contributions.

{% callout "warning" %}**Disclaimer:** Browserhacks is no longer actively maintained. It
remains largely valid, but does not account for latest developments in the CSS
and JavaScript ecosystems. Moreover, using feature detection is preferable to
hacks whenever possible.{% endcallout %}

## What it offers

- **Searchable catalog** of hacks keyed by browser or engine, so you can look
  up techniques for a specific target.
- **Examples and snippets** that can be copied into experiments or debugging
  sessions when you really need to poke at a particular browser’s behavior.
- **Community knowledge** collected in one place instead of scattered across
  blog posts and Stack Overflow answers.

While modern best practice is to avoid relying on hacks wherever possible,
Browserhacks acknowledges that sometimes you need a pragmatic escape hatch —
especially when dealing with legacy environments.

## Historical context

The project became popular at a time when cross‑browser inconsistencies were
much more common, and it has served as both a practical toolbox and a snapshot
of what front‑end developers had to deal with. It has been referenced in talks,
articles and countless debugging sessions over the years.

The site is available at [browserhacks.com](http://browserhacks.com/), with the
data and implementation maintained openly on GitHub.

